  Facebook Prophet — Deep Dive



  What is it?



  Prophet is a time series forecasting library from Meta. It decomposes time series into three components:



  Revenue = Trend + Seasonality + Holidays + Error



  Why Prophet over ARIMA?



  ┌───────────────────────────┬─────────┬──────────┐

  │                           │  ARIMA  │ Prophet  │

  ├───────────────────────────┼─────────┼──────────┤

  │ Requires stationarity?    │ Yes     │ No       │

  ├───────────────────────────┼─────────┼──────────┤

  │ Handles missing data?     │ No      │ Yes      │

  ├───────────────────────────┼─────────┼──────────┤

  │ Multiple seasonalities?   │ Hard    │ Easy     │

  ├───────────────────────────┼─────────┼──────────┤

  │ Interpretable components? │ Hard    │ Built-in │

  ├───────────────────────────┼─────────┼──────────┤

  │ Tuning                    │ Complex │ Minimal  │

  └───────────────────────────┴─────────┴──────────┘



  Interview answer: "I chose Prophet because our data only spans 12 months — not enough for ARIMA to reliably estimate seasonal patterns. Prophet's linear trend model with changepoint_prior_scale=0.05 was conservative enough to not overfit 12 data

  points."



  Key decisions we made



  Excluded December 2011:

  Only 9 days of data. Including it would make November → December look like a massive revenue crash, and Prophet would project that false trend forward.



  No yearly seasonality:

  You need at least 2 full years to fit a yearly seasonal cycle. We only had 1 year — forcing yearly seasonality would have been overfitting noise.



  Linear growth (not logistic):

  Logistic growth requires a capacity cap (the theoretical maximum revenue). We had no business basis for that number. With only 12 months, it produced oscillating nonsense. Linear growth was more honest.

